Yes, you **can** use an `enum` in `wp-config.php`, as long as your PHP version is 8.1 or higher. `wp-config.php` is just a PHP file that runs before WordPress loads, so you can define enums, constants, or functions there.

A few things to keep in mind:

1.  **PHP version:** Make sure the CLI and web server are both running PHP ‚Č• 8.1; otherwise `enum` will cause a fatal error.
2.  **Order matters:** `wp-config.php` is loaded **before WordPress core**, so anything that depends on WordPress functions won‚Äôt work yet. But enums are fine‚ÄĒthey are just PHP types.
3.  **Usage example:**

```
<?php
enum Environment: string {
    case LOCAL = 'local';
    case STAGING = 'staging';
    case LIVE = 'live';
}

// Detect environment
$host = $_SERVER['HTTP_HOST'] ?? 'local.example.com';
$env = match (true) {
    str_contains($host, 'staging') => Environment::STAGING,
    str_contains($host, 'example.com') => Environment::LIVE,
    default => Environment::LOCAL,
};

define('ENVIRONMENT', $env->value);

// Then later in wp-config or your code
if ($env === Environment::LIVE) {
    define('WP_DEBUG', false);
} else {
    define('WP_DEBUG', true);
}
```

4.  **Accessing enum value:** If you need the string, use `$env->value`.

