That‚Äôs a fine setup, but you can **simplify**:

*   If all loggers will share some common behavior (e.g., formatting messages, handling verbosity), you can **fold the interface into the abstract class**.
*   Then subclasses just implement the transport (`writeToFile()`, `writeToConsole()`, etc.) without needing a separate interface.

Example:

```
abstract class MigrationLogger {
    protected int $verbosity = 0;

    public function __construct(int $verbosity = 0) {
        $this->verbosity = $verbosity;
    }

    public function info(string $msg, int $level = 0): void {
        if ($level <= $this->verbosity) {
            $this->write($msg);
        }
    }

    public function warn(string $msg): void {
        $this->write("[WARN] $msg");
    }

    abstract protected function write(string $msg): void;
}

class FileLogger extends MigrationLogger {
    private string $file;

    public function __construct(string $file, int $verbosity = 0) {
        parent::__construct($verbosity);
        $this->file = $file;
    }

    protected function write(string $msg): void {
        file_put_contents($this->file, $msg . PHP_EOL, FILE_APPEND);
    }
}

class ConsoleLogger extends MigrationLogger {
    protected function write(string $msg): void {
        echo $msg . PHP_EOL;
    }
}
```

‚úÖ Benefits:

*   Fewer moving parts: no separate interface needed unless you really want it for type-hinting elsewhere.
*   Shared logic (verbosity, formatting) lives in the abstract class.
*   Easy to extend with new transports (e.g., `DockerLogger`, `MemoryLogger` for tests, etc.).
*   Dry-run runner can just pass a `MigrationLogger` and doesn‚Äôt care about the concrete type.

* * *

