Yes ‚ÄĒ absolutely! A trait is a perfect place for this kind of **reusable project-path and Docker command logic**. That way, any class that needs to run Docker commands can just `use` the trait, and you don‚Äôt have to repeat the boilerplate.

Here‚Äôs an example:

```
<?php
// project/config/UsesDockerPaths.php
declare(strict_types=1);

namespace Project\Config;

trait UsesDockerPaths
{
    private function projectRoot(): string
    {
        return realpath(__DIR__ . '/..'); // adjust if this file moves
    }

    private function dockerDir(): string
    {
        return $this->projectRoot() . '/docker';
    }

    private function envFile(string $env = 'local'): string
    {
        return $this->dockerDir() . "/env/{$env}.env";
    }

    private function composeFiles(string $env = 'local'): array
    {
        return [
            $this->dockerDir() . '/base.yml',
            $this->dockerDir() . "/{$env}.yml",
        ];
    }

    private function buildComposeArgs(string $env = 'local'): string
    {
        $files = $this->composeFiles($env);
        return implode(' ', array_map(fn($f) => "-f " . escapeshellarg($f), $files));
    }
}
```

