Exactly ‚ÄĒ PHP doesn‚Äôt come with a built-in `argparse` like Python does. But you have a few clean ways to handle CLI arguments:

* * *

### **1ÔłŹ‚É£ Use `$argv` manually (simple)**

PHP automatically populates `$argv` in CLI scripts:

```
<?php
$dryRun = in_array('--dry-run', $argv, true);

$source = null;
$target = null;

foreach ($argv as $i => $arg) {
    if ($arg === '--source' && isset($argv[$i+1])) {
        $source = $argv[$i+1];
    } elseif ($arg === '--target' && isset($argv[$i+1])) {
        $target = $argv[$i+1];
    }
}

echo "Dry run: ", $dryRun ? "yes" : "no", PHP_EOL;
echo "Source: $source, Target: $target", PHP_EOL;
```

Pros: Simple, no dependencies.  
Cons: You have to parse options yourself, handle `--help`, defaults, etc.

* * *

### **2ÔłŹ‚É£ Use `getopt()` (built-in, more structured)**

PHP‚Äôs built-in `getopt()` works like classic Unix CLI parsing:

```
$options = getopt('', ['dry-run', 'source:', 'target:']); 
// ':' means the option requires a value

$dryRun = isset($options['dry-run']);
$source = $options['source'] ?? null;
$target = $options['target'] ?? null;

echo "Dry run: ", $dryRun ? "yes" : "no", PHP_EOL;
echo "Source: $source, Target: $target", PHP_EOL;
```

Pros: Clean, handles required arguments, optional arguments, and flags.  
Cons: Doesn‚Äôt do type validation or help text ‚ÄĒ you have to add that manually.

* * *

### **3ÔłŹ‚É£ Use a library (recommended for bigger scripts)**

There are several PHP libraries that behave more like Python `argparse`:

*   [`symfony/console`](https://symfony.com/doc/current/components/console.html) ‚Äď full-featured, supports commands, arguments, options, auto-help, validators.
*   `getopt-php/getopt-php` ‚Äď lighter than Symfony, still structured parsing.

Example with Symfony Console:

```
use Symfony\Component\Console\Application;
use Symfony\Component\Console\Command\Command;
use Symfony\Component\Console\Input\InputOption;
use Symfony\Component\Console\Input\InputArgument;
use Symfony\Component\Console\Input\InputInterface;
use Symfony\Component\Console\Output\OutputInterface;

class MigrateCommand extends Command {
    protected function configure(): void {
        $this
            ->setName('migrate')
            ->addOption('dry-run', null, InputOption::VALUE_NONE, 'Dry run')
            ->addOption('source', null, InputOption::VALUE_REQUIRED, 'Source environment')
            ->addOption('target', null, InputOption::VALUE_REQUIRED, 'Target environment');
    }

    protected function execute(InputInterface $input, OutputInterface $output): int {
        $dryRun = $input->getOption('dry-run');
        $source = $input->getOption('source');
        $target = $input->getOption('target');

        $output->writeln("Dry run: " . ($dryRun ? "yes" : "no"));
        $output->writeln("Source: $source, Target: $target");

        return Command::SUCCESS;
    }
}

$app = new Application();
$app->add(new MigrateCommand());
$app->run();
```

Pros: Structured, scalable, auto-help, validated arguments. Perfect if you‚Äôre growing your `run-migration.php`.

