You don‚Äôt _need_ a `simulate_result()` call at all if you keep the ‚Äúwho simulates?‚ÄĚ rule consistent:

*   **RunnerFactory chooses DryRunExecutor** when `(dry_run && policy === SKIP_EXECUTION)`
*   **DryRunExecutor returns a simulated CommandResult**
*   Artifacts just call `runner->run_operation()` and then do state deltas.

So in the streamlined `run()`, there is nowhere special to ‚Äúcall simulate\_result()‚ÄĚ ‚ÄĒ it happens inside the **executor**.

That said, there are two legit ways to do it, depending on how fancy you want simulation to be.

* * *

Option A (recommended): simulate inside DryRunExecutor
------------------------------------------------------

### Artifact::run() stays simple

```
final public function run(): CommandResult
{
    if (! $this->runner) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("No Runner assigned to artifact: {$this->type->name}");
    }

    $this->validate();

    $result = $this->runner->run_operation($this->operation());

    $this->context->state()->track_result($this->type, $result);

    if ($result->executed && ! $result->succeeded()) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("Artifact failed: {$this->type->name}");
    }

    return $result;
}
```

### DryRunExecutor does the simulating

```
final class DryRunExecutor implements CommandExecutor
{
    public function execute(CliCommand $command): CommandResult
    {
        return new CommandResult(
            command: $command->render(),
            executed: false,
            exitcode: 0,
            stdout: '[dry-run] skipped',
            stderr: '',
        );
    }
}
```

‚úÖ Pros: simplest, no chicken/egg, no per-artifact special cases.

* * *

Option B: per-operation simulation text (still clean)
-----------------------------------------------------

If you want nicer dry-run output (e.g. ‚Äúwould import file X into DB Y‚ÄĚ), add a method to the **operation**, not the artifact.

### RunnerOperation

```
interface RunnerOperation {
    public function to_cli_command(DomainEnvironment $env): CliCommand;

    // Optional: for dry-run executor only
    public function simulate_stdout(DomainEnvironment $env): string;
}
```

### DryRunExecutor can accept the operation instead of CliCommand

This is the only change: the _executor_ needs the operation to get the simulation text.

So change the abstraction slightly:

*   Either:
    *   `CommandExecutor::execute_operation(RunnerOperation $op, DomainEnvironment $env)`
*   Or keep executor as-is, and do simulation in HostRunner (see below)

**Easier:** do it in the HostRunner, because HostRunner has both `$operation` and `$runner_env`.

```
final class HostRunner implements CommandRunner
{
    public function __construct(
        private CommandExecutor $executor,
        private DomainEnvironment $runner_env,
        private bool $simulate_only, // injected by factory based on dry-run policy
    ) {}

    public function run_operation(RunnerOperation $operation): CommandResult
    {
        $cmd = $operation->to_cli_command($this->runner_env);

        if ($this->simulate_only) {
            return new CommandResult(
                command: $cmd->render(),
                executed: false,
                exitcode: 0,
                stdout: $operation->simulate_stdout($this->runner_env),
                stderr: '',
            );
        }

        return $this->executor->execute($cmd);
    }
}
```

Then your factory sets `$simulate_only` when it would have picked DryRunExecutor before.

‚úÖ Pros: best ‚Äúdry-run UX‚ÄĚ, still centralized, still no per-artifact boilerplate.  
‚ö†ÔłŹ Cons: you moved simulation one layer up (runner instead of executor).

* * *

What _not_ to do
----------------

Don‚Äôt put `simulate_result()` in each artifact‚Äôs `run()` or `state_delta()` unless you love repetitive bugs.

* * *

My call for your codebase right now
-----------------------------------

You‚Äôre already in a good groove with **policy ‚Üí executor selection**. So:

*   **Put simulation in DryRunExecutor** (Option A).
*   Add validation in artifacts where it matters (import file exists, etc).
*   Let TOOL\_DRY\_RUN actually run and produce real results.

If later you want prettier dry-run output, upgrade to Option B without touching artifact code.

If you paste your current `DryRunExecutor` and `HostRunner::run_operation()`, I‚Äôll show the exact minimal diff to implement Option A cleanly.

Yep ‚ÄĒ this is the classic dry-run paradox: **the input file is produced by an earlier SKIP\_EXECUTION artifact**, so it won‚Äôt exist.

So the rule has to be:

### In dry-run, ImportDb cannot validate the _file on disk_ ‚ÄĒ it validates the _plan_

Meaning: validate that you _have a coherent reference_ to a planned source backup, and that it _would_ produce a file path.

Concretely, split validation into two layers:

1) Always validate ‚Äúplan invariants‚ÄĚ
------------------------------------

This is what ImportDb can always check in dry-run.

**ImportDb::validate() should check:**

*   The pipeline has a planned/known _source backup path_ (even if not created).
*   That path is non-empty.
*   That path looks sane (ends with `.sql`, under artifacts dir, etc).

That‚Äôs it.

Then:

2) Only validate ‚Äúruntime invariants‚ÄĚ when not dry-run
------------------------------------------------------

Only when the file is supposed to exist do you check existence/readability/size.

* * *

How to implement cleanly
========================

### A) Make state remember the _planned_ backup filename (not only ‚Äúresult‚ÄĚ)

Right now your `db_backup_file()` seems to come from the ‚Äúresult‚ÄĚ (or from pipeline memory you set in result). In dry-run you still want the same filename available.

Do this in the **DB\_BACKUP artifact**:

*   During `operation()` (or wherever you compute `$target_file`), set:

```
$this->context->state()->set_db_backup_plan_file($domain, $target_file);
```

And keep `set_db_backup_file()` for the real result.

So MigrationState has:

```
public function set_db_backup_plan_file(Domain $domain, string $filename): void {
    $this->pipeline_memory['db_backup_plan'][$domain->value] = $filename;
}

public function db_backup_plan_file(Domain $domain): string {
    return $this->pipeline_memory['db_backup_plan'][$domain->value] ?? '';
}

public function set_db_backup_result_file(Domain $domain, string $filename): void {
    $this->pipeline_memory['db_backup_result'][$domain->value] = $filename;
}

public function db_backup_result_file(Domain $domain): string {
    return $this->pipeline_memory['db_backup_result'][$domain->value] ?? '';
}
```

(You can keep your existing `set_db_backup_file()` and just treat it as ‚Äúresult‚ÄĚ; I‚Äôm just making it explicit.)

### B) ImportDb chooses which one depending on dry-run

```
private function import_source_file(): string
{
    $sourceDomain = $this->context->source()->domain();

    return $this->context->dry_run()
        ? $this->context->state()->db_backup_plan_file($sourceDomain)
        : $this->context->state()->db_backup_result_file($sourceDomain);
}
```

### C) ImportDb::validate()

```
public function validate(): void
{
    $file = $this->import_source_file();

    if ($file === '') {
        throw new \RuntimeException("ImportDb: missing source DB backup filename in state.");
    }

    // Always enforce basic sanity
    if (!str_ends_with($file, '.sql')) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("ImportDb: expected .sql file, got: $file");
    }

    if ($this->context->dry_run()) {
        // Do NOT check filesystem; file won't exist in SKIP_EXECUTION dry-run.
        return;
    }

    if (!file_exists($file)) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("ImportDb: file does not exist: $file");
    }
    if (!is_readable($file)) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("ImportDb: file not readable: $file");
    }
    if (filesize($file) === 0) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("ImportDb: file is empty: $file");
    }
}
```

That matches what you _want_: dry-run still catches ‚Äúimpossible plan‚ÄĚ (no file path), but doesn‚Äôt falsely fail on ‚Äúfile isn‚Äôt there‚ÄĚ.

* * *

What should ImportDb dry-run deltas look like?
==============================================

Plan delta should include:

*   `source_backup_file` (the planned filename)
*   `target_domain`
*   maybe `strategy: overwrite`

Result delta in dry-run:

*   include `executed=false` (or `simulated=true` if you add it later)
*   and maybe `note: "skipped"`

Since your `CommandResult::none()` sets `executed=false`, you can just key off that.

* * *

The key mental model
====================

*   **Dry-run SKIP\_EXECUTION artifacts still must compute filenames and write ‚Äúplan‚ÄĚ into state.**
*   **Downstream artifacts read ‚Äúplan‚ÄĚ in dry-run, ‚Äúresult‚ÄĚ in real runs.**

Once you adopt that, analytics-export will also stop being weird: discovery in dry-run needs either TOOL\_DRY\_RUN or a plan fallback.

If you show me your DB\_BACKUP artifact `operation()` + `state_delta()` (just those two), I‚Äôll point to the exact one-liner where you should set the plan filename so ImportDb can depend on it.

