Good question. You don‚Äôt want RFC-lawyer validation. You want **‚Äúwill WP-CLI and MySQL behave predictably with this?‚ÄĚ**

For search-replace, ‚Äúvalid-ish‚ÄĚ means:

1.  Not empty
2.  Has a scheme (`http` or `https`)
3.  Has a host
4.  No trailing whitespace
5.  Not obviously malformed

That‚Äôs it.

* * *

‚úÖ Practical validation rule
---------------------------

Use `filter_var()` but constrain scheme.

```
private function validate_url(string $url, string $label): void
{
    $url = trim($url);

    if ($url === '') {
        throw new \RuntimeException("$label URL is empty");
    }

    $parsed = parse_url($url);

    if ($parsed === false) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("$label URL is malformed: $url");
    }

    if (!isset($parsed['scheme']) || !in_array($parsed['scheme'], ['http', 'https'], true)) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("$label URL must start with http:// or https:// : $url");
    }

    if (!isset($parsed['host'])) {
        throw new \RuntimeException("$label URL has no host: $url");
    }

    // Optional: normalize (helps avoid trailing slash mismatches)
    if (str_ends_with($url, '/')) {
        $url = rtrim($url, '/');
    }
}
```

Call it for both:

```
$this->validate_url($this->source_url, 'Source');
$this->validate_url($this->target_url, 'Target');

if ($this->source_url === $this->target_url) {
    throw new \RuntimeException("Source and target URLs are identical");
}
```

* * *

‚ĚĆ What you should NOT do
------------------------

*   Don‚Äôt try to validate DNS.
*   Don‚Äôt try to validate that the host resolves.
*   Don‚Äôt enforce TLD rules.
*   Don‚Äôt enforce trailing slash rules strictly.

That‚Äôs overkill and will just annoy future-you.

* * *

Optional: normalization (smart move)
------------------------------------

Before storing them, normalize both URLs so you avoid subtle mismatches:

```
private function normalize_url(string $url): string
{
    $url = trim($url);
    $url = rtrim($url, '/');
    return $url;
}
```

Then always use normalized versions for comparison and passing to WP.

* * *

Why this level is correct
-------------------------

Search-replace is fundamentally string replacement.  
You only need to ensure:

*   You‚Äôre not replacing with empty string accidentally.
*   You‚Äôre not replacing `localhost` with `localhost`.
*   You didn‚Äôt typo `htp://`.

Everything else WP-CLI will tell you.

* * *

If you want to be slightly stricter, I can show you a ‚Äúsafe mode‚ÄĚ that also refuses to replace:

*   `https ‚Üí http` on production unless explicitly allowed
*   or replacing to `localhost` unless dry-run

But that‚Äôs optional policy, not validation.



